msgid "Moby Dick"
msgstr ""

#. List: 0
#. EDID: SFFL_SE_EC01_GloriaHomework_MobyDick
#. REC: TMLM:BTXT
msgctxt "000F4C"
msgid "Moby Dick, Obsession, and the Search for Adventure\nBy Gloria Swansen, age 15\n\nHerman Melville's Moby Dick is mostly about Captain Ahab, a man obsessed with revenge who ends up losing everything. His white whale is not just a huge animal that used to live in Earth's oceans, it's his obsession and his doom.\n\nAs I sit in my bunk, listening to the hum of the ship's engines, I stare out the tiny window into the void and think about how Ahab couldn't escape the obsession that pulled him down into the darkness. It reminds me of people I've known, trapped in their own anger, their own pain, until there's nothing left but wreckage. Ahab says: \"my means are sane, my motive and my object mad.\" He believes he is rational just as his obsession takes control.\n\nBut Moby Dick is also about the sea: the unpredictable expanse that can take everything from you but also give you freedom if you know how to navigate it. A way to leave things behind, dangerous but full of possibilities. Ishmael, the protagonist, survives because he learns how to float and move with the waves instead of against them. That's what I want: to keep moving. He says, \"I try all things; I achieve what I can.\" I might not have control over everything, but I can still push forward for something bigger among the stars.\n\nThe ship's engines fire up, preparing for the next jump. Maybe I won't find my adventure today, but I will someday. And when I do, I won't be chasing after something I can never catch. I'll be forging the future."
msgstr ""

#. List: 0
#. EDID: SFFL_SE_EC01_GloriaHomework_MobyDick
#. REC: TMLM:FULL
msgctxt "000F4D"
msgid "Moby Dick Report"
msgstr ""

